Burn-in testing is a process of exercising electronic assemblies under specific conditions (like high temperature or voltage) to force early life failures (infant mortality) to occur before the product reaches the customer. This ensures that the components entering the "useful life" phase of the bathtub curve are less likely to fail prematurely.

According to the bathtub curve model mentioned in the context, early failures occur at the beginning of the life cycle. Burn-in testing is specifically designed to identify these defects early.

